  "prompt": "When having more than one shareholder, how are profits distributed? Monthly, quaterly, after taxes once a year?",
  "response": "The distribution of profits to shareholders can vary depending on several factors including the company's policies, shareholder agreements, and the applicable legal and tax regulations. Generally, profits are distributed as dividends, and this distribution can occur in various frequencies:\n\n1. **Quarterly Basis**: Most publicly traded companies distribute dividends on a quarterly basis. This is a common practice and provides regular income to shareholders.\n\n2. **Annual Basis**: Some companies may opt to distribute dividends annually, often after the annual financial statements have been prepared and taxes have been computed. \n\n3. **Semi-Annually**: There are companies that distribute dividends twice a year, which is referred to as semi-annual dividends.\n\n4. **Monthly Basis**: Though less common, some companies, especially certain types of investment funds or real estate trusts, may distribute dividends monthly.\n\n5. **Interim and Final Dividends**: Companies may choose to distribute interim dividends during the year and then a final dividend after the annual accounts have been completed.\n\nBefore profits are distributed as dividends, the company must pay applicable taxes on its earnings. Additionally, companies may retain some profits for reinvestment in the business or to maintain financial stability.\n\nFor private companies or closely-held corporations, profit distribution may differ as it can be dictated by private agreements between shareholders and the company's specific bylaws. In such cases, the distribution may not follow a regular schedule and could be influenced by the shareholders\u2019 meetings and decisions.\n\nIt is important for shareholders to review the company's dividend policy and any shareholder agreements to understand how and when profits will be distributed.",
